Partly as a result of Risen's revelations, that question now bedevils the Bush administration. It's also one that Isaacson, who is the president and C.E.O. of the Aspen Institute, a public policy center, finds hard to answer. As a former managing editor of Time magazine and chairman of CNN, Isaacson is aware of how the press can and should function, but he is also the author of a biography of Henry Kissinger and the co-author, with Evan Thomas, of ''The Wise Men,'' a study of six policy makers who helped guide the country through the early years of the cold war. ''During my years as a journalist,'' he wrote in an e-mail message, ''one of the most sensitive issues was balancing security concerns with our instinct to report everything we knew. Now, given the terrorist threat, it's even more difficult. I would be inclined these days to hold back information if it could help terrorists. Yet at a certain point, in a constitutional democracy, you need to debate policies that might lead to torture or unauthorized wiretapping. Journalists have an important role in this process, especially when there is little other oversight.'' The Editors

lead_paragraph: THE Commodore looks pretty spiffy, set against the newly cleaned limestone of the south facade of Grand Central Terminal. All brushed up and polished, the four-ton statue of Commodore Cornelius Vanderbilt is half a century older than the 1913 Beaux-Arts building. Actually, it is a mere fragment of a 150-foot-long bronze frieze illustrating the steamship and railroad magnate's accomplishments. Unlike the statue, it has disappeared without a trace. To most people leaving the Holland Tunnel, the wide, barren asphalt spiral between Ericsson Place and Hudson, Varick and Laight Streets is just a wasteland. But in the 1810's, it was one of the most fashionable addresses in New York, or rather the surrounding red brick houses were. The square they bounded was St. John's Park, a landscaped green to which only the householders had keys. Then the fashionable moved farther north, and a railroad line was built down Hudson Street in 1849.
